"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802155","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-11","<p>The current East Coast franchise operated by Virgin Trains East Coast commenced 1<sup>st</sup> March 2015. An announcement of the expected premium over the duration of the contract was made at franchise award. All premiums due to date under the contract have been paid. Payments by franchised operators are published by ORR annually and can be found on their website. We have set out our plans to end the operational divide between track and train, and from 2020 we are establishing the East Coast Partnership, one of the first of a new generation of integrated regional rail operations. This will be subject to a competitive process, and will include appropriate premiums paid from the private partner to the Government.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-11T15:33:32.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802155/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802155/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","East Coast Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 December 2017 to Question 116801, how much Virgin Trains East Coast paid in premium payments (a) from the commencement of the franchise in 2015 to date and (b) will pay in each year until 2023-2024.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","117842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802156","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Franchisee’s Guarantor, Stagecoach Group plc, will be required to meet its financial commitments to the taxpayer in full, in particular the provision of £165m in Parent Company Support which will support payments made by the franchisee to government.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-11T15:49:33.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802156/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802156/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","East Coast Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the Parent Company Guarantee provided by Virgin Trains East Coast for the InterCity East Coast Franchise amounts to; and whether any of that amount will be retained by his Department.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","117843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802157","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-11T18:04:48.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802157/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802157/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Mental Health Services: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the number of (a) hospitals, (b) wards and (c) beds in the mental health sector that have closed in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","117844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802158","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>As the independent regulator of health and social care providers in England, the Care Quality Commission (CQC) regulates and assesses all providers of regulated activities by looking at five domains – whether they are safe, effective, caring, responsive to people’s needs and well-led. These five questions are asked of all the services the CQC inspects. After each inspection, the CQC produces a report. In most cases their reports include ratings, which show their overall judgement of the quality of care.</p><p> </p><p>All of the CQC’s provider ratings are published on the CQC’s website; these can be filtered via the rating and the type of provider. Hospitals currently rated as requires improvement are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.cqc.org.uk/search/services/all?f%5B0%5D=im_field_inspection_rating%3A3927&amp;f%5B1%5D=latest_inspections%3Amonth&amp;f%5B2%5D=im_field_popular_services%3A3672" target="_blank">https://www.cqc.org.uk/search/services/all?f%5B0%5D=im_field_inspection_rating%3A3927&amp;f%5B1%5D=latest_inspections%3Amonth&amp;f%5B2%5D=im_field_popular_services%3A3672</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-11T17:55:16.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802158/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802158/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Hospitals: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the list of hospitals that are rated by the Care Quality Commission as requires improvement overall.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","117845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802159","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>NHS England’s Capacity and Demand Review identified 1,449 children and young people’s mental health inpatient beds (Tier 4) beds at 1 April 2017. The table shows the regions in which these beds are situated.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Region</p></td><td><p>Pre-review position</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>231</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South</p></td><td><p>323</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North</p></td><td><p>404</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Midlands and East</p></td><td><p>491</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National total</p></td><td><p>1,449</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: NHS England</p><p> </p><p>By 2020/21, inappropriate placements to inpatient beds for children and young people will be eliminated: including both placements to inappropriate settings and to inappropriate locations far from the family home (out of area treatments).</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-11T18:03:54.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802159/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802159/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many inpatient mental health beds there are that are suitable for children; and where those beds are situated.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","117846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802160","Scotland Office","false","2017-12-11","<p>I currently have no plans to visit a food bank in my capacity as Secretary of State for Scotland in December 2017.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-12-11T11:33:42.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802160/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802160/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-12-06","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether he plans to visit a food bank in December 2017.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","117847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802161","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>The table below is a count of finished admission episodes with a main or secondary procedure of interventional radiology by Government office region of treatment, for the years 2014-15, 2015-16 and 2016-17. Activity of English National Health Service hospitals and English NHS commissioned activity in the independent sector are included.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Government office region of treatment</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>44,226</p></td><td><p>47,241</p></td><td><p>50,639</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>137,061</p></td><td><p>143,146</p></td><td><p>146,180</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and The Humber</p></td><td><p>88,378</p></td><td><p>92,394</p></td><td><p>96,620</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>58,464</p></td><td><p>63,448</p></td><td><p>66,906</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>93,460</p></td><td><p>96,954</p></td><td><p>99,433</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>94,158</p></td><td><p>98,084</p></td><td><p>102,355</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>155,470</p></td><td><p>163,005</p></td><td><p>173,867</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>128,021</p></td><td><p>138,157</p></td><td><p>147,546</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>78,600</p></td><td><p>85,716</p></td><td><p>86,288</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>877,838</p></td><td><p>928,145</p></td><td><p>969,834</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics, NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p>This data provides a count of the number of interventional radiology procedures, not the number of individual patients as the same person may have multiple procedures.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-11T17:58:29.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802161/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Radiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients underwent an interventional radiology (image-guided surgery) procedure in each region in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","117848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802162","Department of Health","true","2017-12-11","<p>The seven day services self-assessment survey completed by trusts in March 2017 included information on the availability of clinical interventions, including interventional radiology (IR), on a seven day basis for patients admitted to hospital in an emergency. The data showed that <ins class="ministerial">72.30%</ins><del class="ministerial">73.65%</del> of hospital trusts who responded to this survey (<del class="ministerial">109 </del> <ins class="ministerial">107</ins>out of 148 trusts) stated that IR was available for these patients seven days a week.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the twice yearly collection is available on the NHS England website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/seven-day-hospital-services/progress" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/seven-day-hospital-services/progress</a></p><p>National Health Service regions have access to this report and will be able to consider any variation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-11T17:57:45.17Z","2018-01-26T14:08:27.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802162/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802162/answer","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802162/answer/previousversion/28792","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Radiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the NHS’ capacity to deliver 24-hour interventional radiology (image-guided surgery) services in each region.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","117849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802163","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>The seven day services self-assessment survey completed by trusts in March 2017 included information on the availability of clinical interventions, including interventional radiology (IR), on a seven day basis for patients admitted to hospital in an emergency. The data showed that 73.65% of hospital trusts who responded to this survey (109 out of 148 trusts) stated that IR was available for these patients seven days a week.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the twice yearly collection is available on the NHS England website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/seven-day-hospital-services/progress" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/seven-day-hospital-services/progress</a></p><p>National Health Service regions have access to this report and will be able to consider any variation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","117849","2017-12-11T17:57:45.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802163/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802163/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Radiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of regional variation in patient access to interventional radiology procedures (image-guided surgery).","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","117850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802164","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>Specialised Commissioning commissions services that utilise interventional radiology (IR), these include specialised cardiac, hepatology, vascular and cancer services. Where reviews of services are undertaken there is scope to consider comparison between IR and other surgical techniques.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has received the report produced by the Medical Technology Group, ‘Keeping Britain Working: How medical technology can help reduce the cost of ill health to the UK economy’, outlining case studies with the potential to deliver efficiency savings and these have been shared with the relevant commissioning bodies.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-11T17:56:11.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802164/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802164/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Radiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential efficiency savings that could be generated through the use of minimally invasive procedures supported by interventional radiology (Image-guided surgery).","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","117851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802165","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>The information on seven day services and availability of seven day interventional radiology measured in acute trusts in September 2017 is available on the NHS England webpages at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/seven-day-hospital-services/progress" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/seven-day-hospital-services/progress</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-11T17:59:21.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802165/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802165/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Radiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many 24-hour interventional radiology centres there are in each region.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","117852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802166","Department of Health","false","2017-12-13","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>By August 2017 there has been an increase of 844 doctors working in radiology since 2010, equivalent to an increase of 25.2%.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is aware that there is a shortage of interventional radiologists and is working with the Royal College of Radiologists on exploring options to increase access to training and to fast track training for new services such as mechanical thrombectomy.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-13T14:24:50.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802166/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802166/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Radiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of full-time equivalent interventional radiologists; and what assessment he has made of whether there are adequate numbers of interventional radiologists to deliver 24-hour services.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","117853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802167","Department of Health","false","2017-12-13","<p>This information is not held centrally. National data is held on the total number of day beds available across a wide number of clinical interventions.</p><p> </p><p>The latest data for Quarter 2 of 2017/18 shows the average daily number of day only beds was 12,379.</p><p> </p><p>Further data surrounding bed availability is published online by NHS England at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/bed-availability-and-occupancy/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/bed-availability-and-occupancy/</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-13T14:19:31.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802167/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802167/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Radiology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of day beds available to interventional radiology patients.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","117854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802168","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>Seafarer qualifications are issued and recognised in accordance with the international convention on the Standards of Training, Certification and Watch-keeping (STCW) 1978, as amended. This is an international Convention that is applicable to all seafarers working at sea. The UK will continue to recognise seafarer qualifications in accordance with procedures set out in the Convention.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-12T15:55:18.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802168/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802168/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Shipping: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on the mutual recognition of seafarer qualifications with EU member states after 29 March 2019.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","117855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802169","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>Since May 2010, no Maritime and Coastguard Agency official has visited other countries specifically to advise them on seafarer training standards.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-12T15:57:42.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802169/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802169/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Shipping: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many times officials from the Maritime and Coastguard Agency have visited another country to advise on seafarer training standards since May 2010; and what the dates and destinations were of each such visit.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","117856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802170","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>The gathering of material for the review has been completed and a report is currently being prepared. Publication is expected early in 2018.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-12T15:52:46.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802170/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802170/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress is being made on his Department's review of the Maritime Growth Study.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","117857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802171","Department for Education","false","2017-12-11","<p>We do not collect information about schools’ timetables and therefore we do not hold this information. We have placed phonics at the heart of the curriculum and introduced the phonics screening check at age six to help identify children that need additional help with their reading. In 2017, 81% of pupils nationally met the expected standard at the end of year 1, up from 58% in 2012. In Northamptonshire, the figure was also 81%, up from 55% in 2012. Thanks to our reforms and the hard work of teachers and pupils, an additional 154,000 six year olds across England are on track to become fluent readers.</p><p>In addition, the 2016 Progress in International Reading Study results, published last week, put the success of our increased emphasis on phonics and continued focus on raising education standards on a global scale. England rose up the rankings from joint 10<sup>th</sup> in 2011 to joint 8<sup>th</sup>, and achieved the highest performance since the study began in 2001, driven by an increase in the number of low-performing pupils reading well.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-11T17:22:07.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802171/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802171/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-06","Reading: Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of primary school children have daily reading lessons in (a) England and (b) Northamptonshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","117858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802172","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>The information requested is not held.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-12T15:49:43.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802172/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802172/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Shipping: Crew","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many UK seafarer (a) Ratings and (b) Officers held jobs on vessels which have joined the UK Ship Register since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","117859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802173","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>As of 8 December 2017, there are (a) 483 vessels on the UK Ship Register that are beneficially owned outside of the UK; and (b) 181 vessels on the UK Ship Register which are managed outside of the UK.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-12T15:59:51.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802173/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802173/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Shipping: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many vessels on the UK Ship Register are (a) beneficially owned and (b) managed outside the UK.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","117860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802174","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>The UK Ship Register (UKSR) is promoting the UK Flag advantages to UK and eligible international owners of some of the largest fleets of quality ships in various sectors, including tankers, bulk carriers, container and passenger ships. In addition, the UKSR has enhanced its customer service, can now provide Maritime and Coastguard Agency Marine Surveyors 24/7, and has placed a Marine Surveyor in Singapore.</p><p>Other steps will include digitisation of services (Registration and Seafarer Documents) which will be rolled out in 2018/19. These changes will encourage UK and international ship owners to register their vessels with the UKSR.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","118024","2017-12-12T16:02:33.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802174/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802174/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Merchant Shipping: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to encourage UK ship owners to register merchant vessels on the UK Ship Register.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","117861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802175","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>No recent estimate has been made.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-12T15:46:35.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802175/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802175/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Shipping: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of the (a) minimum and (b) maximum cost to industry of legislation prohibiting nationality-based pay discrimination in the UK shipping industry.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","117862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802176","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-14","<p>Factors that a farmer takes into account when deciding where to send stock may include the proposed method of slaughter. Where a farmer has signed up to an assurance scheme, there will be some additional assurance as to the slaughter methods being used under those schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Where farmers want to know the method of slaughter used at a particular plant, the information should normally be provided by the plant and it would be the farmer’s choice if they sell their stock to that abattoir.</p><p> </p><p>In all slaughterhouses there are strict rules that govern the slaughter of animals in England and the Government will take robust enforcement action against animal welfare breaches when they are identified.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-14T15:37:53.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802176/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802176/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-06","Slaughterhouses: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will take steps to ensure that farmers know the method of proposed slaughter for their animals before they agree to sell them.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","117863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802177","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-13","<p>The three neonicotinoids covered by the EU restrictions are currently authorised for use in the UK on the following 25 crops: wheat; barley; oats; rye; durum wheat; triticale; sugar beet; fodder beet; potato; carrot; swede; ornamental plants; forest nursery; broccoli/calabrese; brussels sprout; cabbage; oriental cabbage; cauliflower; endive; kale; lettuce; apple; pear; hops and nursery fruit trees.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-13T18:22:45.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802177/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802177/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-06","Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent estimate he has made of the number of crops on which neonicotinoids have been used; and if he will list those crops.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","117864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802178","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-15","<p>It is a key priority of this Government to enable an innovative, productive and competitive food supply chain which invests in its people and skills.</p><p> </p><p>Defra Ministers have ongoing discussions with a range of government departments, including the Home Office, about securing the workforce that the farming industry, needs for the future.</p><p> </p><p>After we leave the EU, we must have an immigration system which works in the best interests of the UK – controlling immigration whilst continuing to welcome those who make an invaluable contribution.</p><p> </p><p>For the longer-term the Government has commissioned the independent Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) to assess the role that EU citizens play in the UK economy and society.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-15T12:00:54.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802178/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802178/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-06","Horticulture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that farmers have access to a sufficient number of workers to work in the horticultural industry after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","117865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802179","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-15","<p>My Department works closely with the Home Office and is also engaged with the National Police Chiefs’ Council on Wildlife Crime and Rural Affairs and the National Rural Crime Network.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-15T12:25:37.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802179/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802179/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-06","Rural Areas: Crime Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Home Secretary on reducing the incidence of rural crime.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","117866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802180","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-11","<p>Representations were received, in writing and during meetings, from (fifteen) industry representative bodies and (four) businesses.</p><p>The Government will shortly be publishing a response to the Trade White Paper, including a summary of responses received.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-12-11T17:19:28.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802180/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802180/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-12-06","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 5 December 2017 to Question 116918 on energy intensive industries: trade agreements, if he will list the 19 organisations from which he received representations on the implementation of trade remedy measures; and what plans he has to publish the details of those representations.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","117867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802181","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-11","<p>The roles will be advertised with a salary of up to £120,000, dependent on the skills and experience of the candidate, which is within the Senior Civil Servants pay band 2 range of £88,000 to £162,500. The successful candidates will also be entitled to overseas allowances, to compensate for the extra costs incurred from moving overseas and maintaining a standard of living comparable to the UK. The rates are dependent on the location and family circumstance.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-12-11T17:21:37.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802181/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802181/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-12-06","Trade Promotion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 5 December 2017 to Question 116660 on trade promotion, what estimate he has made of the total employment cost per annum of the nine Her Britannic Majesty's Trade Commissioners.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","117868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802182","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-12","<p>I can confirm that since 1 January 2015, 2,115 staff have left my Department (of which 59% was inter-Civil Service movement).</p><p> </p><p>The Civil Service does not routinely collect information on the nationality of civil servants. The information requested is not held.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-12-12T15:58:37.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802182/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802182/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-06","Cabinet Office: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many members of staff have left his Department since 1 January 2015; and how many of those members of staff were nationals of non-UK EU countries.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","117869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802183","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-11","<p>Information on Ministerial travel is published on a quarterly transparency return on ww.gov.uk.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","117914 ; 117931 ; 117970","2017-12-11T17:35:15.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802183/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802183/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-06","Military Aircraft: Ministers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which Government Ministers have used RAF aircraft on official business for what purposes on what dates since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","117870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802184","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-14","<p>The Internet Safety Strategy consultation closed on 7 December. We are now analysing the responses and we will be working with technology companies, charities and other interested stakeholders to develop the code of practice. We will consider plans to monitor uptake and observance of the code of practice ahead of its publication in 2018.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-14T12:20:49.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802184/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802184/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-06","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer 28 November to Question 113183, how her Department plans to monitor uptake and observance of the code of practice for social media companies provided for in the Digital Economy Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","117871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802185","Department of Health","false","2017-12-14","<p>There are no plans to instruct National Health Service trust and clinical commissioning groups to collect data on the children with incontinence problems.</p><p> </p><p>However, as part of business planning for 2018/19, Public Health England is reviewing whether the new section dedicated to child and maternal health on their Fingertips digital platform would be a suitable place to make data about childhood continence available at a local level.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-14T14:29:42.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802185/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802185/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-06","Incontinence: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will instruct NHS trusts and Clinical Commissioning Groups to start compiling data on the numbers of children with incontinence problems.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","117872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802186","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Foreign Secretary has discussed the issue with the US Secretary of State Tillerson, most recently on 5 December. The Prime Minister set out the UK's position on the US decision in her statement of 6 December.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-18T16:55:09.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802186/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802186/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-06","Jerusalem","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the US Administration on its decision to recognise Jerusalem as the capital of Israel.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","117873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802187","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-18","<p>The Government has regular discussions with National Grid across a range of energy matters, including investment in the UK. As the electricity Transmission Owner for England and Wales, National Grid is investing approximately £9 billion over the current RIIO price control period of 2013-21. Over the same period, National Grid is investing £2 billion in the gas transmission network. National Grid Ventures, National Grid’s commercial development arm separate from the core regulated business, is investing around £2 billion in new electricity interconnectors, including the 1 gigawatt (GW) Nemo Link to Belgium, the 1 GW IFA2 link to France, and the 1.4 GW North Sea Link to Norway. It is also planning further links, including the 1.4 GW Viking Link interconnector to Denmark.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-18T12:49:29.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802187/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802187/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-06","National Grid plc","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the National Grid on its investment portfolio and its plans for future investment in the UK.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","117874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802188","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>The estimates of the environmental benefits included in Table 8-5 were calculated in accordance with the Department for Transport’s (DfT’s) processes for appraising transport investments. The economic appraisal, including the environmental impacts reported in Table 8-5, was carried out using the DfT’s Transport Analysis Guidance, where environmental benefits (including noise, local air quality, and greenhouse gasses) are monetised and assessed over a 60 year appraisal period.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-12T15:26:29.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802188/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802188/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 7 November 2017 to Question 110602, on Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification, how the estimate of the environmental benefits included in Table 8 – 5 were calculated.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","117875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802189","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-14","<p>Local authorities already have very broad compulsory purchase powers, which can be used to support the delivery of a range of development and infrastructure projects. Through both the Housing and Planning Act 2016 and Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017, the Government is taking forward a substantial package of reforms to make the compulsory purchase process clearer, fairer and faster for all.</p><p>We are keen for local authorities to make use of these new provisions, which include replacing often conflicting case law on compulsory purchase compensation with a clearer basis for identifying market value. This will allow negotiations on compensation to proceed with more speed and certainty. We will keep the operation of these reforms under review and consider whether further reforms are necessary.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-14T17:08:15.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802189/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802189/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-06","Compulsory Purchase","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to review and enhance local authorities' compulsory purchase powers.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","117876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802190","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-12","<p>We are committed to improving journeys for passengers on the Midland Main Line, which is why we are delivering biggest upgrade of the route since it was completed in 1870. The upgrade will enable increased passenger capacity and reduced journey times, and will see modern trains introduced across the route, including a fleet of brand new bi-mode intercity trains from 2022. The Government has made this decision to deliver benefits for intercity passengers sooner than would otherwise be possible.</p><p> </p><p>In line with the Department for Transport’s (DfT’s) processes for appraising transport investments, an economic appraisal including the environmental impacts has been carried out, using the DfT’s Transport Analysis Guidance and incorporating DEFRA guidance on transport related environmental impacts. The results of the appraisal show that compared to the do-minimum scenario, which was continued diesel operation with the existing fleet for 10 years and then the introduction of bi-modes in 2030/31, introducing bi-modes straightaway to replace diesels delivers £11m of greenhouse gas emission savings over the 60-year appraisal period, whilst fully electric trains would have delivered £271m of greenhouse gas savings over the same period.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-12T15:34:28.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802190/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802190/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-06","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 7 November 2017 to Question 110602, what assessment he has made of the environmental effect of using bi-mode trains on the Midland Mainline on the basis that the line beyond Kettering will not be electrified.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","117877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802191","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Strike Experimentation Group (SEG) was established in Warminster in April 2017 and is part of the headquarters of 1st Armoured Infantry Brigade. This will build and develop understanding of the Strike concept within the brigade and its units. The SEG has engaged with Allies, including in the US, France, Canada and Italy, to develop opportunities for combined experimentation and knowledge exchange. They have also developed some early tactics for operational analysis by the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory, and conducted a battlegroup level live experiment with the Canadian Army to investigate armoured cavalry techniques using a surrogate for the Ajax vehicles.</p><p>Since the statement on refinements to the Army's structure by the then Secretary of State for Defence on 15 December 2016 [HCWS367], the Army has made minor changes to the sequencing of units to form Strike. The 1st Armoured Infantry Brigade will become the first Strike Brigade by 2020. It will comprise the Household Cavalry Regiment, the Royal Dragoon Guards, 1st Battalion Scots Guards, and 3rd Battalion The Rifles.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-12-11T17:57:39.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802191/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802191/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-06","Strike Experimentation Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent progress has been made on establishing the Strike Experimentation Group.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","117878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802192","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-18","<p>No local authorities will be affected by negative revenue support grant (nRSG) in the financial year 2018-19. Additional resources have been allocated to eliminate nRSG in 2017-18 and 2018-19.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-18T17:57:56.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802192/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802192/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802192/answer/previousversion/30451","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-06","Revenue Support Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and which local authorities he estimates will receive a negative revenue support grant in the financial year 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","117879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802193","Women and Equalities","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Government Equalities Office and its Ministers are in regular contact with the Equality and Human Rights Commission on a range of issues to do with the running of the Commission.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","117881 ; 117883","2017-12-11T17:37:39.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802193/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802193/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-12-06","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many times she has (a) met, (b) spoken to and (c) communicated with (i) directly with or (ii) through (A) officials, (B) Ministerial advisers and (B) other contacts, the Chair of the Equality and Human Rights Commission in the last 12 months.","true","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","117880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802194","Women and Equalities","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Government Equalities Office and its Ministers are in regular contact with the Equality and Human Rights Commission on a range of issues to do with the running of the Commission.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","117880 ; 117883","2017-12-11T17:37:39.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802194/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802194/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-12-06","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, on what dates she (a) met, (b) spoken to and (c) communicated with (i) directly with or (ii) through (A) officials, (B) Ministerial advisers and (B) other contacts, the Chair of the Equality and Human Rights Commission in the last 12 months.","true","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","117881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802195","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-12","<p>The Department for International Development has robust measures in place to protect, prevent, and detect the diversion of aid. We have controls embedded through-out the programme cycle, from design through mobilisation, delivery and closure; this includes a rigorous due diligence process and a comprehensive risk management framework which requires risks to be identified prior to any disbursement of aid.</p><p>All organisations that receive funding from DFID are required to provide evidence about the use of funds, including audited financial statements which are examined as we monitor programme performance and delivery. All of our funding mechanisms allow DFID to terminate funding projects early if suppliers do not fulfil their obligations. DFID uses the UK Partnership Principles which are a set of 4 principles to assess partner governments. These include a commitment to respect human rights, and in particular the civil, social and cultural rights of poor or marginalised people.</p><p>We have a zero tolerance approach to aid diversion and this applies to all those within the delivery chain who are entrusted with UK aid. When aid diversion is identified DFID will always work to recover UK taxpayers’ money.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-12T18:09:07.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802195/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802195/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-12-06","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that UK development assistance does not end up in the hands of terrorist groups or regimes that persecute LGBT people, religious minorities or minority ethnic groups.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","117882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802196","Women and Equalities","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Government Equalities Office and its Ministers are in regular contact with the Equality and Human Rights Commission on a range of issues to do with the running of the Commission.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","117880 ; 117881","2017-12-11T17:37:39.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802196/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802196/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-12-06","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, on what dates between (a) 20 March and 21 April 2017 and (b) since 21 April 2017 (i) she, (ii) Officials of her Department, (iii) Ministerial advisers or (iv) others (A) met with, (B) spoke to or (C) communicated with the Chair of the Equality and Human Rights Commission; and on which of those dates contact with the Chair of the Equality and Human Rights Commission included communication about (I) the position of Disability Commissioner on the Equality and Human Rights Commission or (II) Lord Shinkwin.","true","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","117883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802197","Women and Equalities","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Government Equality Office and its Ministers are in regular contact with the Equality and Human Rights Commission on a range of issues to do with the running of the Commission. These discussions and communications are not routinely published.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-11T17:35:48.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802197/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802197/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-12-06","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, if she will publish communications relating or referring to (a) the position of Disability Commissioner on the Equality and Human Rights Commission and (b) Lord Shinkwin between (i) herself, (ii) Officials of her Department, (iii) Ministerial advisers, (iv) the Government Equalities Office, (v) the Equality and Human Rights Commission and (vi) David Isaac between (A) 20 March and 21 April 2017 and (B) since 21 April 2017; and if she will place copies in the Library.","true","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","117884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802198","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-14","<p>The Department for International Trade’s (DIT) Northern Powerhouse (NPH) Investment Taskforce, established in 2016 after consultation with partners in the north, undertakes three primary activities: its 5 sector specialists research and collate the commercial strengths of the north and showcase these to target investors; it briefs DIT’s network in 108 countries on these NPH strengths, through webinars and inward visits, so the network can talk knowledgeably and passionately about the NPH with investors; and it supports existing foreign investors in growing their business in the UK by providing a framework and funding for local partners to key account manage companies which are not already on DIT’s key account management framework.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-12-14T09:40:19.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802198/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802198/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-12-06","Foreign Investment in UK: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to increase the amount of foreign direct investment in the North of England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","117885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802199","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-14","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) leads on Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) policy.</p><p>DIT has been working closely with colleagues in the BEIS Industrial Strategy team, to ensure the closest possible alignment of activity to support the Strategy’s initiatives around growing clusters and sectors, and the promotion of FDI through DIT’s FDI strategy.</p><p>This will deliver a more targeted approach to promotion and investor support, and better address market failures to maximise wealth creation across the UK. From April 2018, we will change our measure of performance from the volume of projects landed to a comprehensive measure of economic impact.</p><p>Alongside this DIT will work with local partners to identify High Potential Opportunities that are currently overlooked, misunderstood, or underestimated, and therefore not achieving their full potential. Targeted promotion and support around these opportunities will help to address the market failures that leave these places at a disadvantage, by presenting investors with a more complete picture of supply.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-12-14T13:10:24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802199/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802199/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-12-06","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how his Department is working with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy to attract foreign direct investment into the Industrial Strategy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","117886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802202","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-15","<p>The starting point for decisions by local planning authorities and planning inspectors will be the approved development plan for the area taking into account relevant material considerations, including national planning policy and guidance. All housing allocations and infrastructure plans need to be deliverable.</p><p>Where a Local Planning Authority (LPA) has not delivered sufficient completions in previous years against its housing requirement this will result in a shortfall of supply against the five year land supply. The preferred approach (as set out in Planning Guidance) to addressing past shortfalls is to ensure they are met within a five year period (known as the Sedgefield method), but LPAs have argued at both examinations and appeals that due to their particular circumstances they need to meet the past shortfalls over the whole plan period. Inspectors have considered the most appropriate approach on a case by case basis.</p><p>To ensure that the guidance on five year land supply is suitably clear, transparent and comprehensive, the Government committed in the Housing White Paper to issue new guidance.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","117891 ; 117894 ; 117897","2017-12-15T12:38:07.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802202/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802202/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-06","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if a (a) local planning authority, and (b) planning inspector, is able to consider as a material planning consideration, the likelihood of a local planning authority making up a shortfall identified in its five year supply of deliverable housing sites in later years in an (i) existing Local Plan; and (ii) emerging Local Plan, when determining planning application.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","117889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802203","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Mechanised Infantry Vehicle (MIV) initial gate business case has now been approved, moving the project into the assessment phase.</p><p>The assessment phase will focus on confirming the optimum fleet mix and delivery sequence.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","117892","2017-12-11T17:57:09.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802203/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/802203/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-06","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 4 December 2017 to Question 116496, whether the Mechanised Infantry Vehicle program is in the assessment phase.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","117890"
