"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800919","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-12","<p>We do not hold specific data on referrals to disability programmes. However, we are committed to ensuring people with disabilities are systematically included in our programme portfolio, and we are asking all our partners to do more to disaggregate data by disability. Examples of programmes we support which directly benefit people with disabilities include:</p><ul><li>Tailored education for students with special needs in the Occupied Palestinian Territories, either through incorporation into mainstream schooling or referral to specialised teaching (delivered through United Nations Relief and Works Agency).</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Specialised psychiatric care, protection for children traumatised by violence or conflict, and cash assistance for families with a family member who has mental health issues (delivered through International Medical Corps).</li></ul>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-12T15:55:23.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800919/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800919/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-12-05","Middle East: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2017 to Question 115249 on Refugees: Disability, what information her Department holds on  the number of referrals made to the disability programmes the UK Government is supporting in that region.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","117478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800921","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Department has been closely monitoring this tragic case and we will be considering whether there are any wider implications for product safety in light of the Coroner’s Report and Whirlpool’s formal response to the Coroner, which is due by 26<sup>th</sup> December.</p><p>The Government’s response to the Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety will consider the recommendations made in their Report in July. Our response will consider any factors that are relevant to improving the system of product safety and recalls so that consumers can have confidence in the safety of electrical products.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-11T15:10:12.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800921/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800921/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-05","Domestic Appliances: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department plans to take into account the Regulation 28: Report to prevent future deaths by David Lewis, Assistant Coroner for the area of North Wales (East and Central) on the Llanrwst fire inquest when it responds to the report from the Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","117480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800922","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-11","<p>In delivery of the JSA New Claim service the Provider has received and accepted complaints that equate to 0.003% of the total Customer interactions, which is comparable with services delivered internally.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-12-11T16:56:21.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800922/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800922/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-05","Jobcentres: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent representations he has received on the effect on benefit claimants of outsourcing jobcentre telephony work to Capita.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","117481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800923","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-11","<p>We are committed to continuing to build work coach capability to deliver personalised and tailored support. All work coaches across the Jobcentre Plus network receive training on supporting people with health conditions and disabilities and we have developed an enhanced mental health training programme, which is now available in every country and region across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the roll out of the Health and Work Conversation across the UK supports work coaches to continue to build engagement with claimants with disabilities and health issues, backed by comprehensive new training which builds skills of empathy and active listening. We have also recruited new disability employment advisers and community partners who are in place in every country and region of the UK.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-11T12:09:48.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800923/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800923/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-05","Employment: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's response to the consultation, Work, health and disability: improving lives, what plans his Department has to improve mental health training for frontline staff in each region of the UK.","true","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","117482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800924","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-11","<p>In March 2015 the Government published research that the Department for Transport commissioned from York Aviation entitled “The Economic Value of General Aviation in the UK”. That research contained an estimate of the jobs linked to the general aviation sector in the UK being 38,000. York Aviation did not separate out the contribution from the Government’s STEM (Science, Technology Engineering and Mathematics) education programmes.</p><p> </p><p>We are commissioning research on what a strategic network of general aviation airfields might look like and this research may review that calculation. We expect this research to report in 2018.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-11T14:09:09.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800924/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800924/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-05","Aviation: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the contribution to growth and employment in the STEM sector made by the general aviation sector in the UK.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","117483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800925","Department of Health","false","2017-12-12","<p>Under the Children and Families Act 2014, clinical commissioning groups, National Health Service trusts, NHS foundation trusts and local education providers must co-operate with the local authority in supporting children with a special educational need, such as autism. This includes the sharing of relevant information. The statutory guidance Special educational needs and disability code of practice:0 to 25 years issued jointly by the Department of Health and the Department for Education, provides advice on how the partners can work together and share information in their statutory roles. The two departments have also issued a guide to the Code specifically for clinical commissioning groups, health professionals and local authorities.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-12T14:49:08.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800925/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800925/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-05","Autism: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department has issued on the sharing of information between medical and educational professionals following a diagnosis of autism for a young person.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","117484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800926","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-11","<p>As my Rt Hon Friend is aware, the planning inquiry into these proposals is scheduled to open on 12 December. It will consider all relevant matters and these will be taken fully into account by the Secretary of State on receipt of the Inspector’s report.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-11T17:06:33.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800926/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800926/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-05","Planning Permission: Hatfield Peverel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of (a) the detrimental impact on the countryside and (b) the additional pressures on public services in Hatfield Peverel caused by development proposals when he considers the planning applications APP/Z2610/V/17/3180725, APP/Z2610/V/17/3180729 and APP/Z1510/W/16/3162004, called in for him to determine","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","117485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800927","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>Officials are currently reviewing the report by the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs entitled Commissioning impact of on drug treatment published on 6 September. The Government will respond shortly.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-11T17:39:29.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800927/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800927/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-05","Drug: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs report Commissioning impact on drug treatment which published in September 2017, what assessment he has made of the effect of reductions in funding for local authorities on the availability of drug misuse treatment in England.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","117486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800928","Department for Education","false","2017-12-13","<p>The role and remit of the Social Mobility Commission is set out in legislation. There are no current plans to change the functions of the Commission and we intend to begin the public appointments process for a new Chair and Commissioners in due course.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-13T17:47:07.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800928/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800928/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-05","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the role and remit of the Social Mobility Commission will be upon appointment of its new Board.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","117487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800929","Department for Education","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Department for Education is fully committed to the work of the Social Mobility Commission. We value the wide-ranging work carried out by the Commission, including its research programme, its State of the Nation annual reports, and both the Social Mobility Index and the Social Mobility Employer Index.</p><p>The government has previously allocated the following funding to the Commission:</p><ul><li>£600,000 in 2015-6.</li><li>£589,000 in 2016-7.</li><li>£610,000 in 2017-8.</li></ul><p>Future funding allocations have not yet been agreed and will be decided by the Department for Education, in consultation with the Commission, at the appropriate time. This is in accordance with normal procedures for non-departmental public bodies.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-11T16:20:10.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800929/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800929/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-05","Social Mobility Commission: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding was allocated to the Social Mobility Commission from the public purse in (a) 2015-16, (b) 2016-17, (c) 2017-18; and how much such funding is planned to be allocated in (i) 2018-19, (ii) 2019-20 and (iii) 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","117488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800930","Department for Education","false","2017-12-11","<p>We welcome the Social Mobility Commission’s State of the Nation annual reports. They are wide-ranging, valuable pieces of work that support this government’s commitment to social mobility.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission’s analysis has been an important input to the department’s work on social mobility.</p><p> </p><p>We are investing £72 million in 12 Opportunity Areas in order to focus effort on areas of the country with the greatest challenges and fewest opportunities. All 12 of these were social mobility coldspots identified by the Commission in its Social Mobility Index published in 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Social mobility is the department’s priority and we are making good progress across a range of areas. We will be spending around £6 billion per year on childcare and early education support by 2019-20. The attainment gap between disadvantaged pupils and their peers has narrowed since we introduced the Pupil Premium – now worth around £2.5 billion per year - in 2011. Young pupils from disadvantaged areas are now also entering universities at record rates.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-11T16:32:54.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800930/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800930/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-05","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which recommendations the Government adopted from the Social Mobility Commission's State of the Nation Report (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","117489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800931","Department for Education","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Department for Education is fully committed to the work of the Social Mobility Commission. We plan to begin the public appointments process for a new chair and commissioners in due course. This is a public appointment, and the process will be completed following the procedures set out in the Public Appointments guidance.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-11T16:16:04.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800931/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800931/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-05","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the timetable is for (a) new Commissioners, (b) a new Chair and (c) a new Vice-Chair to be appointed to the Social Mobility Commission.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","117490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800932","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>The proposals as set out in the Green Paper would cost £215 million over the next three years towards the creation of Mental Health Support Teams (including to train and employ the new workforce), piloting a four week waiting time standard and rolling out mental health first aid training in primary schools. Funding will be made available to take forward the proposals following the consultation. As set out in the Impact Assessment which was published alongside the Green Paper, £15-20 million will also be made available, by the Department for Education, each year from 2019 for significant training programmes for schools and colleges until all schools and colleges have had the opportunity to train a Designated Senior Lead for mental health.</p><p> </p><p>However, it is worth noting that specifics around the proposals, which may impact on the cost estimates provided above and set out in the impact assessment, will be determined post consultation. The outcome of the trailblazer phase will also inform future roll-out and costs.</p><p> </p><p>Funding decisions for the Green Paper proposals after the current spending review ends in 2020/21 will be subject to future spending reviews.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-11T18:00:51.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800932/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800932/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-05","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to his Department's proposals in its Green Paper on children and young people's mental health, published on 4 December 2017, if he will publish a breakdown of spending areas in each year to 2022-23 for the additional expenditure committed.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","117491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800933","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-11","<p>We have read and considered the Disability Benefits Consortium's recommendations with regards to Health Professionals who carry out PIP assessments. Independent reviews form an important part of the learning process and we are constantly looking to improve the experience of claiming PIP. We recognise the scale of the challenge in implementing a new benefit so committed to two, statutory independent reviews of PIP. The latest of these reviews, led by Paul Gray, was published on 30 March 2017 and we plan to respond to this later this year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department encourages claimants to provide as much relevant evidence as necessary to support their claim. Before claimants are invited for a face-to-face consultation, all of the available evidence is reviewed and if, at that stage, advice to the Department can be made on this evidence alone, the claimants will not be required to attend a face-to-face assessment.</p><p>We continue to work extensively with the PIP assessment providers and disability representative groups to make improvements to guidance, training and audit procedures in order to ensure a quality service.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-11T17:29:43.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800933/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800933/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-05","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will assess the merits of implementing the Disability Benefits Consortium's recommendations on PIP assessors.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","117492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800934","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-11","<p>There is an existing process for those claimants of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) who wish to record their assessments which is publicised on the websites of both assessment providers and reflects the guidance in Part 1 of the PIP Assessment Guide (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/personal-independence-payment-assessment-guide-for-assessment-providers#history" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/personal-independence-payment-assessment-guide-for-assessment-providers#history</a>).</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-11T11:38:04.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800934/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800934/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-12-05","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to allow Personal Independence Payment claimants to have their assessments recorded.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","117493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800935","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-13","<p>The Government is committed to a system of better regulation that supports well-targeted and effective regulations which protect the public.</p><p> </p><p>Our Industrial Strategy, published on 27th November, sets out our commitment to working with businesses to inform development of an agile approach to regulation that promotes and supports innovation, growth of new sectors and the requirements of innovative market entrants – while ensuring effective protections for citizens and the environment.</p><p> </p><p>We are strengthening our horizon scanning, including through a new Ministerial Working Group on Future Regulation, to help us identify arising regulatory issues and priorities for future work. As my Rt Hon Friend, Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, announced at Budget, we will also support a new £10m Regulators’ Pioneer Fund to help regulators to develop innovative approaches aimed at getting new products and services to market.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-13T15:44:07.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800935/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800935/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-12-05","Business: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 29 November 2017 to Question 115913, if he will list the Government's programmes aimed at reducing regulation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","117494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800936","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Government is planning to use the EU (Withdrawal) Bill to transfer into domestic law the EU schemes that currently protect our geographical indications (GIs). This will ensure that UK GIs remain protected in the UK after we leave the EU. Defra officials are working closely with officials from other government departments, the devolved administrations, and the Crown Dependencies on this.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-11T19:56:39.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800936/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800936/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-05","Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to decide whether protected geographical indicators will continue after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","117495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800937","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Ministry of Justice and <em>Her Majesty's Prison and Probation Service (HM</em>PPS) takes seriously the ongoing challenges that substance misuse poses to our establishments and we continue to implement a range of measures to address both the availability and use of such harmful substances. This is based on a multi-agency approach working closely with health partners and law enforcement agencies.</p><p> </p><p>The data for part (a) of the question is only available from October 2015, when a new enhanced incident reporting standard was introduced that allowed better recording of items found, including the type of person who possessed the items found. Data is in the table shown in Annex A of this answer.</p><p> </p><p>The data for part (b) of the question will be reflected in the number of positive random mandatory drug tests. This is published in Table 7.2 within the supplementary tables at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017.</a> It is important to note that some prisoners may be tested more than once in this period.</p><p> </p><p>Prisons have at their disposal a range of security measures to reduce the supply of drugs into prisons including physical searching, the use of x-ray machines, CCTV surveillance cameras, intelligence-led searches as well as drug detection dogs. HMPPS have trained more than 300 dogs to detect PS and these dogs are available to all prisons. HMPPS are also exploring additional innovative security measures and new technology to complement existing searching methods in prisons.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-12-11T15:38:49.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800937/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800937/answer","Annex A PQ 117496 .doc","Annex A ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800937/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-05","Prisoners: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners have been found (a) in possession and (b) under the influence of drugs in each of the last seven years in each region of England.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","117496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800938","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-11","<p>Security is our top priority. If anyone attempts to undermine our security we will do whatever is necessary to ensure prisoners are secure.</p><p>Since 2010 there have been 9 relocks at a total cost of £529,973.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Time Frame</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Cost (excluding VAT)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010 - 2011</p></td><td><p>£337,553</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011 - 2012</p></td><td><p>Cost Met by private contractor operating the prison</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012 - 2013</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 2014</p></td><td><p>£28,812</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 2015</p></td><td><p>£46,396</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 - 2016</p></td><td><p>£117,212</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 - 2017</p></td><td><p>Cost Met by private contractor operating the prison</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>The figures quoted have been drawn from live administrative databases and may subsequently be amended. Due care is taken during processing and analysis, but the detail is subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale recording system.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-12-11T17:41:01.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800938/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800938/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-05","Prisons: Locks and Keys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information his Department holds on the number of occasions when, due to the loss or theft of keys, a prison has had to be relocked since March 2010; and what the cost to the public purse was of each such incident.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","117497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800939","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-13","<p>We have worked closely with the Parole Board to help them progress cases more quickly, and to eliminate the backlog of delayed cases by the end of this year. This should lead to a decrease in the number of compensation claims in future years.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided additional funding for 100 new Parole Board members – a near 60% increase - and established a dedicated MoJ unit to help progress complex cases. We are ensuring prisoners can secure release by showing genuine progress while fulfilling our most important duty - protecting the public</p><p> </p><p>The amount of compensation paid to prisoners as a result of delays in parole hearings in the years 2009/10 - 2016/17 is set out below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Amount</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>£30,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£49,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£243,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£87,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£91,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£144,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£554,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-12-13T16:12:12.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800939/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800939/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-05","Prisoners: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much compensation has been paid to prisoners as a result of delays in parole hearings in each year since March 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","117498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800940","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-12","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-12-12T12:46:15.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800940/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800940/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-12-05","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been paid in compensation to (a) prisoners, (b) prison staff and  (c) third parties as a result of injuries suffered in a violent attack on the prison estate in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","117499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800941","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-12","<p>​The United Kingdom understands that a Communiqué was issued by the Senior Divisional Officer (SDO) of Manyu District (South-West Region) on 1 December ordering villagers to relocate to safer neighbourhoods. The High Commissioner in Yaoundé is following events in the Anglophone regions closely and has actively raised the need for dialogue and restraint with the Cameroonian authorities, including their obligations under international law in respect to human rights. We continue to call for restraint, for all parties to reject violence, pursue peaceful, inclusive and purposeful dialogue, and urgently take action to reduce tensions.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-12T18:13:32.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800941/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800941/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-05","Cameroon: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on a Communique sent to the Anglophone population of Southern Cameroon on its being required to evacuate its villages.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","117500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800942","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-12","<p>Our High Commission in Yaoundé continues to follow events in the Anglophone regions closely, meeting opposition groups, human rights defenders and the Cameroonian authorities. The lack of verifiable information on the human rights situation, including allegations of rape, makes it difficult to give an accurate assessment. However, the High Commissioner will continue to raise our concerns with the Cameroonian authorities, including Cameroon's obligations under international law in respect to human rights. The British Government condemns sexual violence in conflict and is working with foreign governments, the United Nations, African Union, and international organisations to end it.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-12T18:16:36.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800942/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800942/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-05","Cameroon: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the human rights situation in Cameroon.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","117501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800943","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-13","<p>Our High Commissioner in Yaoundé has raised our concerns about the situation in the Anglophone region, including their obligations under international law in respect to human rights, with Prime Minister Philemon Yang and the Secretary General of the Presidency on 22 November. In these and several other recent meetings with Cameroonian Ministers, he called on the Cameroonian Government to exercise restraint, enter into purposeful and inclusive dialogue and to take action to reduce tensions. The High Commissioner will continue to raise our concerns, including Cameroon's obligations under international law in respect to human rights, with the Prime Minister and others members of his government.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-13T08:56:27.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800943/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800943/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-12-05","Cameroon: Genocide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 4 November 2017 to Question 110340, whether he plans to make further representations to the Prime Minister of Cameroon on reports of genocide in that country.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","117502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800945","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-14","<p>We believe that Shared Ownership has an important role to play as part of a diverse and thriving housing market and since 2010 around 54,000 new Shared Ownership homes have been delivered.</p><p>We continue to work with the sector and lenders to ensure that Shared Ownership continues to be attractive to investment and have made a number of changes to support this, including expanding the Affordable Homes Programme from £7 billion to over £9 billion, standardising eligibility for buyers and extending funding for development to private providers.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-14T17:04:57.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800945/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800945/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-05","Shared Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that there is adequate private investment in shared ownership accommodation.","false","Biography information for Neil O'Brien","Harborough","Neil O'Brien","117504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800946","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-13","<p>There are many types of different transactions, and government has not made a comprehensive assessment of the potential for reduction in the cost of payment transactions, or the effect of such changes on financial inclusion.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Government is taking action to drive down the cost of transactions. As an example, the interchange fee regulation (which came into force in December 2015 and caps one of the costs associated with card) is thought to have saved businesses c£500m in transaction costs<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>, and is encouraging firms to pass on this saving to customers.</p><p> </p><p>From 13 January 2018, for most retail payments, merchants will also not be able to add a surcharge just for using a particular payment instrument.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also supporting competition in payments to drive down costs. The second Payment Services Directive (PSDII) will provide for greater competition by creating a regulatory regime for new payment initiation services, which are generally lower cost than card services.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, in 2015, the Government established the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR) in 2015, with statutory objectives including promoting competition and innovation, and ensuring that user needs are taken into account.</p><p> </p><p>[1] According to analysis by the British Retail consortium</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-12-13T16:58:05.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800946/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800946/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-05","Financial Services: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the (a) potential for reduction in the cost of payments transactions and (b) effect of changes in that cost on financial inclusion.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","117505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800947","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-18","<p>Under the Investment Regulations 2016, administering authorities in the Local Government Pension Scheme are no longer constrained by central prescription on how their assets are invested provided investments are in the best interests of scheme members. They now have much greater freedom to invest, subject to local democratic control and appropriate safeguards, and significant investment in new housing has already been made.</p><p>Our Housing White Paper encourages further investment more widely in housing, including shared ownership, through creating a stable financial environment in which to invest.</p><p>As a result, pension schemes are increasingly regarding housing as an appropriate investment. The pooling of local government pension funds will increase opportunities for their assets to be used to support infrastructure projects, including housing. This could generate promising returns for scheme members while maintaining value for money for national and local taxpayers.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-18T11:53:55.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800947/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800947/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-05","Local Government: Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that local government pension funds can invest in areas such as new build shared ownership.","false","Biography information for Neil O'Brien","Harborough","Neil O'Brien","117506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800948","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-11","<p>DFID does not allocate its research budget geographically by region. Allocation is based on priority themes set out in the 2016 Research Review. In 2016-17 DFID spent £321 million on research (which classifies as science expenditure). DFID funded research partnerships span different regions and multiple countries, with the highest footprint of research taking place in East and West Africa.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-11T16:09:21.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800948/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800948/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-12-05","Department for International Development: Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of her Department's science budget is allocated to (a) the UK,  (b) Africa and (c) Asia.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","117507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800949","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-13","<p>We take both the protection of personal data and the right to privacy extremely seriously. The Data Protection Bill will make our data protection laws fit for the digital age in which an ever increasing amount of data is being processed. It will empower people to take control of their data and support UK businesses and organisations through the change.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-13T16:31:56.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800949/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800949/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-05","Computer Software","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the implications of third-party tracker in Android apps for the security and privacy of UK citizens.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","117508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800950","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-11","<p>The £28 million announced at Autumn Budget 2017 will help support the victims of the Grenfell tragedy and communities in North Kensington. £10 million of this funding will provide additional mental health support, £3 million for providing a new community space, and £15 million will be invested in the Lancaster West Estate.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-11T17:11:31.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800950/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800950/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-12-05","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the grant for Kensington and Chelsea Council announced in Autumn Budget 2017 for people affected by the Grenfell Tower fire is allocated to (a) mental health services, (b) developing new community spaces and (c) regeneration projects.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","117509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800951","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-11","<p>I have regular discussions with Ofwat across a range of water policy issues, including leakage.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's Strategic Policy Statement (SPS) to Ofwat, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661803/sps-ofwat-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661803/sps-ofwat-2017.pdf</a> sets out that we expect companies to cut leakage. The SPS also expects Ofwat to promote ambitious action to reduce leakage and per capita consumption, where this represents best value for money over the long term, including exploring setting targets in future.</p><p> </p><p>Ofwat has already suggested in its draft methodology that it expects companies to justify their proposals against options, including a 15% reduction by 2025, or upper quartile performance on leakage per property per day. The draft methodology can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://064f1d25f5a6fb0868ac-0df48efcb31bcf2ed0366d316cab9ab8.ssl.cf3.rackcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Delivering-Water-2020-Consulting-on-our-PR19-draft-methodology-2.pdf" target="_blank">https://064f1d25f5a6fb0868ac-0df48efcb31bcf2ed0366d316cab9ab8.ssl.cf3.rackcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Delivering-Water-2020-Consulting-on-our-PR19-draft-methodology-2.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-11T13:06:24.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800951/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800951/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-05","Water Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with Ofwat on ensuring water and sewerage companies improve their response to leakages.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","117510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800952","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>Data on the rates of prostate cancer among men over 50 are not held in the format requested.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-11T17:37:22.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800952/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800952/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-05","Prostate Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of trends in the rates of prostate cancer among men over 50 who are (a) white and (b) BAME during the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","117511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800953","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-11","<p>In the last three years, as a result of DFID support, 18.4 million people have pledged to end Female Genital Mutilation (FGM). Two additional countries (Nigeria and the Gambia) have introduced criminal legislation and the largest ever Africa-led movement on FGM has been formed.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-11T09:53:40.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800953/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800953/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-12-05","Africa: Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what progress her Department has made on eliminating female genital mutilation in Africa in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","117512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800954","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Treasury does not hold any information on the change in number of financial advisors who offer advice on personal pensions arising from recent changes on accessibility to personal pensions. The regulation of financial advisors is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-12-11T11:55:38.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800954/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800954/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-05","Personal Pensions: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on the change in number of financial advisors who offer advice on personal pensions arising from recent changes on accessibility to personal pensions.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","117513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800955","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-11","<p>The UK has committed £400 million from 2013 to 2019 to the Global Polio Eradication Initiative.</p><p> </p><p>The final UK disbursement to the Initiative is scheduled for September 2019. These funds will be used as part of the final global push to eradicate polio.</p><p> </p><p>This information can be found on the Development Tracker- https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk/</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-11T18:01:40.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800955/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800955/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-12-05","Developing Countries: Poliomyelitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the amount of funding allocated to the Global Polio Eradication Initiative which will not be spent by 2019.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","117514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800956","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-11","<p>We are working to ensure a smooth transition for the chemical industry as we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The European Union (Withdrawal Bill) will convert existing EU chemicals law, including REACH, into domestic law wherever practical, giving consumers and businesses as much certainty as possible. The UK is strongly committed to the effective and safe management of chemicals. That will not change when we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Negotiations are still ongoing regarding future trade arrangements, and it would not be appropriate to pre-judge their outcome.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-11T17:51:09.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800956/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800956/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-05","Chemicals: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has for regulation of the chemical industry in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","117515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800957","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-11","<p>We are unable to provide information on the costs of registrations as the fee structure for registration depends on a number of different factors. For example, the fee structure for registration is determined by both the size of the registrant company and the tonnage band of registration. We do not have access to the data to analyse the registrations further to be able to assign costs.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-11T13:13:15.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800957/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800957/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-05","Chemicals: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the cost of REACH registration fees paid by UK chemicals industry companies in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","117516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800958","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-12","<p>The Civil Service Nationality Rules are specific to the Civil Service and govern the eligibility of individuals to be employed in the Civil Service on the grounds of their nationality. These rules are distinct from rules governing immigration status, i.e. the right to live/work in the UK, which all employers must comply with.</p><p> </p><p>The Civil Service Nationality Rules reflect a range of legislation, including The Act of Settlement 1700, The Aliens Restriction (Amendment) Act 1919, the Aliens’ Employment Act 1955, The British Nationality Act 1981 and European law. The Cabinet Office is working closely with the Home Office and DExEU to ensure that these rules continue to be operable as broader legislative decisions are made in preparation for the UK leaving the EU.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-12-12T15:54:52.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800958/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800958/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-05","Civil Servants: Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of possible changes required to the Civil Service nationality rules to address the provisions relating to freedom of movement after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","117517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800959","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-12","<p><strong>The Civil Service does not routinely collect information on the nationality of civil servants. The information requested is not held centrally.</strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","117519","2017-12-12T15:53:45.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800959/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800959/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-05","Civil Servants: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he has made an assessment of the civil service functions across central government that have the highest reliance on non-UK EU nationals; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","117518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800960","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-12","<p><strong>The Civil Service does not routinely collect information on the nationality of civil servants. The information requested is not held centrally.</strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","117518","2017-12-12T15:53:45.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800960/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800960/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-12-05","Government Departments: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he has made an estimate of the number non-UK EU nationals employed by each Government Department as a (a) civil servant and (b) contractor.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","117519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800961","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The information requested is already published and can be found at</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/dataset/driving-licence-data" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/dataset/driving-licence-data</a></p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-11T15:55:02.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800961/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800961/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-05","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) men and (b) women hold a (a) full and (b) provisional UK driving licence.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","117520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800962","Department of Health","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Infant Formula and Follow-on Formula Regulations 2007 implements European Commission Directive 2006/141/EC on infant formulae and follow-on formulae, which gives effect to the principles and aims of the 1981 World Health Organization Code on the Marketing of Breastmilk Substitutes dealing with marketing, information and responsibilities of health authorities. There are no plans to review this legislation after the United Kingdom leaves the European Union.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-11T17:40:18.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800962/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800962/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-05","Infant Foods: Marketing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health what assessment he has made of the potential merits of fully implementing the International Code of Marketing of Breastmilk Substitutes after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","117521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800963","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-11","<p>The UK continues to press for a VAT zero rate for women’s sanitary products at EU level so that we can introduce at the earliest opportunity, consistent with the United Kingdom’s EU obligations.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-12-11T13:59:25.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800963/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800963/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-05","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer what progress is being made on abolishing VAT on sanitary products.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","117522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800964","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-12","<p>Data for waste arisings and treatment are not structured specifically around material streams so we cannot provide detailed information on the destination of total food waste. Large tonnages of both incinerated and landfilled waste are reported as “mixed” waste categories, for which we do not currently have estimates of food waste content.</p><p> </p><p>Estimates of biodegradable municipal waste landfilled are published in the Defra UK Statistics on Waste publication, with the latest release containing data for 2010-2015. The estimated tonnages of biodegradable municipal waste landfilled in the UK in 2013, 2014 and 2015 were 9.3 million, 8.7 million and 7.7 million tonnes respectively.</p><p> </p><p>We do not publish data on the composition of municipal solid waste that is received at incineration. However, it is estimated that the amounts of biodegradable municipal waste incinerated in England in 2014, 2015 and 2016 were 3.8 million, 4.6 million and 5.6 million tonnes respectively.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-12T15:48:42.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800964/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800964/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-05","Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the amount of (a) food waste and (b) total bio-degrable waste that goes to (i) incineration and (ii) landfill in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","117523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800965","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-11","<p>Stoke-on-Trent's bid to be UK City of Culture 2021 was assessed by an independent judging panel, chaired by Phil Redmond, along with the ten other bids to host the title. The bid was assessed as strong and was shortlisted on that basis. The panel reconvened on 6-7 December 2017 for the final stage of the selection process and recommended that Coventry should be awarded the title of UK City of Culture 2021. The unsuccessful bid teams will receive detailed feedback on their bids to help inform and shape their future cultural plans.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-12-11T14:28:04.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800965/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800965/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-12-05","UK City of Culture: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the strength of Stoke-on-Trent's bid to be UK City of Culture 2021.","false","Biography information for Jack Brereton","Stoke-on-Trent South","Jack Brereton","117524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800966","Home Office","false","2017-12-12","<p>Section 19 of the Gangmasters Licensing Act 2004 makes provision for the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority (GLAA) to share information relating to gangmasters with any person for the purposes of, or for any purpose connected with the exercise of its functions under the Act.</p><p>This power is also underpinned by operational protocols that have been developed between relevant departments and agencies.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2017-12-12T17:35:58.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800966/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800966/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-05","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether a Memorandum of Understanding or similar document is in place for the sharing of data obtained by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority with her Department; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","117525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800967","Home Office","false","2017-12-12","<p>Since the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority (formerly the Gangmasters Licensing Authority) became operational in 2006, it has passed 653 intelligence reports to the Home Office relating to persons, businesses or general information where there may be an immigration interest.</p><p>This information is only shared in relation to those suspected of committing a labour market offence and does not include details of victims.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2017-12-12T17:36:48.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800967/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800967/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-12-05","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have had their data shared by the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority with her Department for immigration enforcement purposes since that authority was established.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","117526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800968","Department for Education","false","2017-12-13","<p>Parents will remain able to retract nationality and country of birth information previously submitted through the school census for the remainder of the current academic year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-13T17:21:36.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800968/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800968/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-05","Schools: Census","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress is being made on the review of parents’ right to retract nationality and country of birth data submitted through the school census; and whether parents will still be able to retract this data by responding that they refused in the Spring census.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","117527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800969","Department for Education","false","2017-12-13","<p>Nationality data is not used in the data matching process that matches Department for Education data with the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>The current Memorandum of Understanding between the Department and the Home Office, which was revised in October 2016, is in the House Library.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-13T17:20:39.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800969/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800969/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-12-05","Pupils: Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and the Home Office published in December 2015, whether nationality data is used in the data-matching process that matches her Department's records with Home Office records submitted to it.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","117528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800970","Department of Health","false","2017-12-13","<p>I have portfolio responsibility for the commissioning of non-urgent patient transport.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-13T14:00:40.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800970/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800970/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-12-05","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which Minister of his Department has responsibility for non-emergency patient transport.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","117529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800971","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-13","<p>Decisions on allocations to Departments for replacement EU funding are yet to be taken. This includes the European Maritime and Fisheries Fund. Decisions will be made in light of wider UK strategic priorities and other domestic spending decisions.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-12-13T16:34:55.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800971/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800971/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-12-05","Common Fisheries Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which Department will be allocated funds repatriated from the Common Fisheries Policy after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","117530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800972","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-12","<p>The tariff rates applied to the commodities named vary considerably among WTO members and in relation to the specific product being traded. The tariff applicable to UK exports after the UK leaves the European Union will thus depend on the destination of those exports. Full information on WTO members’ tariffs is available on the tariff data pages of the WTO website.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-12T15:16:04.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800972/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800972/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-12-05","Meat: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the level of WTO tariffs for (a) beef (b) poultry (c) sheep (d) pork exports from the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","117531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800973","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-13","<p>To date, the Government’s Office for Low Emission Vehicles (OLEV) has provided more than £100 million to support the installation of uni-directional chargepoints. The Department has not made an estimation of the cost and the number of uni-directional chargepoints that will be installed in the UK by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>As announced at Budget 2017, a new £400m electric car Charging Infrastructure Investment Fund (£200m new Government investment to be matched by private investors) will accelerate the roll-out of charging infrastructure by providing access to finance to companies that deliver chargepoints.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that Vehicle to Grid (bi-directional) charging capability could become an important service for our energy system, but is still at a relatively early stage of development. OLEV and the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy are providing funding of £20 million for innovative projects that develop future Vehicle to Grid products, services and knowledge. The outcome of these projects will help inform future development of bi-directional charging.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","117533 ; 117535 ; 117539","2017-12-13T15:28:39.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800973/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800973/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-12-05","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to the public purse to date has been of installing or subsidising (a) uni-directional and (b) bi-directional charge points for electric vehicles in the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","117532"
