"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800975","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-11","<p>'Cannibalisation' is the routine maintenance practice of removing and recycling spare parts that are taken from one aircraft to be used on another, to ensure the maximum number of aircraft are available to meet the Typhoon flying requirement.</p><p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-12-11T18:00:17.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800975/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800975/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-12-05","European Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on how many occasions the RAF has cannibalised Typhoon aircraft due to lack of available spares in order to keep up with operations and training programmes over the last (a) three, (b) six and (c) 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","117534"
